]]> Thu, 22 Jun 2023 21:38:03 +0000 <![CDATA[May Newsletter]]> https://mailchi.mp/manybabies/2023-may-newsletter https://mailchi.mp/manybabies/2023-may-newsletter May Newsletter MB committees, new resources, project updates

May 2023

Highlights

  • World premiere: What is ManyBabies?

  • Join a ManyBabies committee!

  • Open Data workshop recording available now

  • Project updates

watch and share:

What is ManyBabies?

Join an MB committee

We are looking for individuals to join our committees! This is a great way to contribute to the overarching goals of ManyBabies and network with MB colleagues via a minimal time commitment
(~2 hours/month).  

 

Teaching Training, & Open Science  

Meets monthly to develop teaching and training materials for ManyBabies and the broader developmental science community. Recent efforts include the ManyBabies Workshop Series, as well the production of the “What is ManyBabies?” intro video. 


Diversity & Outreach

Meets monthly to consider ways to promote respectful inclusion, diversity, and outreach in ManyBabies projects. Recent efforts have focused on creating guidelines for inclusive zoom meetings and developing a survey that will enable developmental scientists from around the world to learn about one another’s research.
 

Additional committees

Ethics; Statistics, Analysis, & Code Review


Interested? email contact@manybabies.org

More information about MB committees available here

MB Workshop: Open Data

RECORDING AVAILABLE NOW

Announcements

 

MB Student Advisor noms

Nominations for Student Advisor are due TOMORROW, 31 May 2023!
View more info here »

Open Science Listening Sessions 

The White House is hosting a series of listening sessions with Early Career Researchers over the next 2 weeks to discuss the possibilities of Open Science. Open to all (including non-US residents)
View more info and register here »

MB Drop-In Hours

Thursday 1 June, 3-4pm UTC


Zoom links in the MB Calendar

Project Updates

Data Collection: 
MB2, MB3, MB4

There is still time to sign up »

Join project channels on Slack for support with data collection issues.

MB3: Rule Learning

We are currently working on our analysis pipeline. If you enjoy working with Github, R, and related tools, please contact Ingmar Visser or Cátia Oliveira to join.

The follow-up studies have begun planning (MB3L) and data collection (MB3T). Please contact Anna Exner if you would like to join either effort. 

MB4: Social Evaluation

As of this morning, 43 labs are collecting data (with 5 finished!) from 19 countries (Australia, Austria, Canada, China, Colombia, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Israel, Italy, Japan, Korea, Netherlands, New Zealand, Poland, Serbia, Switzerland, US). We extended our data collection deadline to the end of October 2023. We are still recruiting new labs to join us in data collection this summer; please help us spread the word by sharing our sign up information.

MB5: Hunter & Ames model

We are happy to report that we have received very positive reviews on our Stage 1 Registered Report from Nature Human Behaviour. The leadership team is currently taking a first pass through the reviews, and we will be sharing them with the community for input soon. Updates on stimulus development and other next steps were recently shared via the project listserv – make sure you are subscribed to stay up to date!

MB-Demographics

The revised manuscript has been resubmitted to Developmental Psychology. Thanks to all team members for your hard work!

MB-ManyWebcams

We received overall positive feedback from reviewers at Infancy and were invited to submit a major revision. We are currently working on the manuscript and response letter. Contributors: the deadline to contribute to the manuscript revision is June 5.

ManyManys

ManyManys is organizing an Open Webinar on Reversal Learning in August 2023! (exact date and time TBA). Details will be shared soon on our website. Do not miss out on this unique opportunity to learn, collaborate, and be part of the ManyManys 1 Project!

Reminders

Join the MB Slack

Report MB activities


If you have an announcement or event you would like included in a future issue, email us!

]]> Tue, 30 May 2023 17:15:27 +0000 <![CDATA[Call for Nominations - Student Advisor]]> https://mailchi.mp/manybabies/2023-callfornoms https://mailchi.mp/manybabies/2023-callfornoms Call for Nominations - Student Advisor
Call for nominations for MB Student Advisor

2023

Call for nominations:

 

ManyBabies
Student Advisor

About the position

The role of Student Advisor (SA) was created to ensure that the student perspective is fully considered in ManyBabies’ organizational decision making. ‘Student’ here is defined as anyone not yet having completed their PhD or a comparable degree (acknowledging that doctoral candidates may not be considered students everywhere).

The primary responsibility of the MB Student Advisor is to attend monthly 1-hour Governing Board meetings and participate in leadership discussions to ensure the student perspective is represented. In addition, the SA will have the opportunity to be involved with other leadership roles, such as sitting on specialized ManyBabies committees.

Our inaugural SAs will be completing their term in June and we are issuing a call for nominations for their successor(s). The one year term is non-renewable, although SAs might be invited to continue on in another capacity.
 

Nomination process

Individuals may nominate themselves or others as candidates for the SA position. Those nominated by someone else will be contacted by the Executive Director to determine whether they choose to accept the nomination. We especially encourage nominees from groups currently under- or not represented in MB general leadership (e.g., located outside of US/Canada, from historically marginalized communities). 
Nominations should include a short blurb – no more than 100 words – about qualifications and/or why the nominee would be a good candidate for the role. Links to papers or websites are welcome as part of this blurb.

Please send all nominations to
manybabies@manybabies.org 
(subject line: SA nomination)

Nomination deadline: May 31, 2023

 

Selection process

The Student Advisor(s) will be selected by the Governing Board – including outgoing Student Advisors – no later than June 15, 2023, with an expected term start of July 2023 (exact date contingent on Governing Board meeting schedule).

In selecting the SA, consideration will be given to diversity (see above), interest in open science practices, and qualifications as presented in the nomination blurb.
 

Important Dates

Note: dates subject to change; any changes will be publicized
 
  • Nomination deadline: May 31, 2023

  • SA selection: by June 15, 2023

  • Term start for new members: July, 2023

Please direct any questions to MB’s Executive Director, current SAs Francis Yuen and Mary Beth Neff, or any member of the Governing Board: https://manybabies.org/people/ 

 

 

Please share and encourage others to submit nominations for themselves or others!
Copyright © 2023 ManyBabies, All rights reserved.

]]> Mon, 24 Apr 2023 13:00:00 +0000 <![CDATA[MB Workshop: Open data for develomental science]]> https://mailchi.mp/5c094e88c2d7/mb-workshop-open-data-for-develomental-science https://mailchi.mp/5c094e88c2d7/mb-workshop-open-data-for-develomental-science MB Workshop: Open data for develomental science Join us for a free virtual workshop on open data!

ManyBabies Workshop:

Open data for
developmental science


May 11, 2023 8:30-10:00am CEST (UTC +2)

Dr. Christina Bergmann

Osnabrück University of Applied Sciences & Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics

Open data is one of the key mandates in calls for increased transparency, with badges, citation advantages, and sometimes even refusal to publish papers when data are not made open. For developmental researchers, this need for transparency stands in stark contrast with confidentiality, especially when working with infants. Christina will review developmental science’s impressive history of open data to show that there are ways to ethically and responsibly share data, and then discuss different strategies and emerging best practices to balance participant protection with transparency.

 

Note: The workshop will be recorded and shared with registrants.
REGISTER

View recordings of previous MB workshops
on our YouTube channel

]]> Wed, 19 Apr 2023 17:11:49 +0000 <![CDATA[Authorship survey and panel]]> https://mailchi.mp/f9021476351a/authorship-survey-and-panel https://mailchi.mp/f9021476351a/authorship-survey-and-panel Authorship survey and panel Fill out our author survey and attend a BTS authorship panel

Take the

ManyBabies authorship 
Help us understand your experiences with and expectations of authorship with ManyBabies. We want to know what works and doesn't work about the way completed and current projects have handled authorship, and how we can improve the way we do this in the future.

If you have contributed to a ManyBabies project, please take a few minutes to complete the short survey.
Take the survey

Attend the

INSciTS Big Team Science 
Authorship Panel

Linking SciTS and Big Team Science to Advance Complex Collaborations


Wednesday, April 5th, 2023

9:00am (PDT), 12:00pm (EDT), 6:00pm (CET)
Register to attend

The rise of big team science has vitalized conversations about how scientific contributions are recognized and rewarded. This panel will discuss challenges with this complex area of research as detailed in Coles et al., (2022; 2023), with an emphasis on one of the central issues in these conversations – what constitutes authorship in science. Perspectives on authorship vary both within and between individual researchers, scientific organizations, publishers, and science stakeholders. Three panelists from big team science initiatives will review their perspectives and experiences with these issues–and audience members will be encouraged to submit additional questions and join the conversation.
Copyright © 2023 ManyBabies, All rights reserved.

ManyBabies Workshop:

Reproducible Writing Using R Markdown

March 21 @ 9:00-10:30 PDT (San Francisco)
Join Mike Frank from Stanford University to learn how to use R Markdown to produce fully reproducible manuscripts, and never worry about copy/paste errors again! 
REGISTER NOW!

MB "Drop-In" Hours

Thursday, March 2, 16:00-17:00 & 23:00-24:00 UTC


Stop by for any reason, or for no reason at all!

announcements

Manuscript Invitation for Special Issue

 
Attention all Developmental Scientists!
Click here to learn more about a special issue of Infancy, on Developmental Plasticity in Early Human Development. Please note that letters of intent must be submitted by April 1, 2023. Authors will be notified by May 1, 2023 of any invitation to submit a full manuscript, with a full submission deadline of August 1, 2023.


Survey about non-USA

publishing experiences

 
Developmental science researchers who are based outside the U.S.A. and conduct studies on non-U.S.A. samples are invited to fill out a short survey about publishing experiences including peer review and feedback from editors. The survey is available in English, takes around 7-8 minutes to complete, and all responses will be anonymous. The survey can be accessed until March 7, 2023 here. If you have any questions, please contact Rowena Garcia.

(survey presented by Dana Basnight-Brown, Bobby Cheon, Rowena Garcia, Melanie Killen, Reiko Mazuka, & Leher Singh)

Boyd McCandless Award Nominations

Nominations are still open for the APA Boyd McCandless Award for Early Career Contribution to Developmental Psychology. 

Nomination deadline: March 15, 2023

project updates

MB3: Rule Learning

 

upcoming meetings:

 

MB3L and MB3T Spin-offs meeting

March 6 @ 14:00 UTC
See calendar for more details & contact Anna Exner with questions
 

MB3 check-in meetings

March 7 @ 8am & 4pm UTC
Check the listserv or #mb3-general channel on the MB Slack for more info!
 

MB3 analysis team meeting

March 13 @ 14:00 UTC
See calendar for more details

MB4: Social Evaluation

31 labs from 15 countries have officially signed up, pledging to collect data of at least 638 infants! The number has reached our goal to reach 80% power to compare the Social to the Non-Social condition (Nmin = 500). The sign-up number for the individual differences spin-off project has also made a breakthrough and reached at least 358 infants.

We are still recruiting more labs to increase the power of our Bayesian analyses and the diversity of our sample. Join us!

MB6: Neonatal Imitation

The first team-wide MB6 meeting will be held on March 22 @ 15:30 UTC, and all are welcome! Make sure you are subscribed to the project listserv to receive an invite.

January 2023

highlights

  • New MB Preprints (MB1T, MB5, MB-Demographics, MB-ManyWebcams)

  • Data collection updates

announcements

ICIS Founding Generation Summer Fellowship

Now Accepting Applications!


ICIS is offering a limited number of grants to support undergraduate student research in infancy science during the summer of 2023. Learn more here.

Student application deadline: February 14, 2023

Boyd McCandless Award Nominations


Nominate your favorite early-career scientist for the APA Boyd McCandless Award for Early Career Contribution to Developmental Psychology. 

Nomination deadline: March 15, 2023

Contribute to FORRT's
Replications & Reversals project


FORRT’s “Replications & Reversals” project aims to collate successful replications, failed replications with null findings, and failed replications with reversals in the social sciences. They are in need of info about developmental replication efforts!
You can find more info on how to contribute to the project here.

events
Register here
Early bird rates end on February 2nd. 
If you are attending SRCD and would be interested in organizing a ManyBabies meet-up, let us know!

MB "Community Drop-In Hours"

Thursday, February 2, 16:00-17:00 & 23:00-24:00 UTC


Stop by for any reason, or for no reason at all!
Zoom links are in the MB calendar

project updates

MB1T: Test-Retest spin-off

The manuscript has been submitted to Developmental Science and is currently under review! The preprint can be found here. Thanks to everyone who contributed to the manuscript!

MB2: Theory of Mind

We are in the midst of our data collection phase. In parallel, the MB2 analysis team is preparing the analysis pipeline (3 hackathon days so far). Interested in joining the analysis team? Contact Tobias Schuwerk.

MB3: Rule Learning

We are very excited to share that several labs have been ‘greenlighted’ and that hence MB3 data collection has officially started! The official starting date for data collection has been set to January 1, 2023 and the tentative end date is therefore December 31, 2023.

For data collecting labs:

  • The data validator is now online and ready to use! Instructions are in the MB3 lab manual. 
  • If your lab has the flexibility of choosing between different set-ups, please consider HPP.
  • We are planning two MB3 check-in meetings on March 7 for labs to ask questions and discuss progress. (check the listserv or #mb3-general channel on the MB Slack for more info)

MB3 Longitudinal & Test-Retest Spin-off 

We are very excited to announce the launch of an MB3 spin-off project. 

In a first step, we aim to answer the question to what extent the methods from the MB3 project are suitable to measure individual differences in infants' rule learning abilities by investigating test-retest reliability. In a second step, we aim to investigate the relationship between infants' rule learning abilities and their later developing language acquisition skills.

We are looking for enthusiastic people and labs who would like to join this project! If you are interested in joining the design team or contributing in other ways, please contact Anna Exner.

MB4: Social Evaluation

Data collection is underway! We are still welcoming new contributors to collect data with us. If you are interested, please check out our website and complete our sign up form.

MB5: Hunter & Ames Model of Infant Looking Preference

The Stage 1 Registered Report is under review at Nature Human Behaviour (read the preprint). Thank you to everyone who contributed to the manuscript! 

MB6: Neonatal Imitation

The first team-wide MB6 meeting will be held soon, and all are welcome! Make sure you are subscribed to the project listserv to receive scheduling information. 

MB-Demographics:

Our manuscript has been submitted to Developmental Psychology. You can read the preprint here. Thank you to all who contributed to the project! 

MB-ManyWebcams:

We finished our manuscript and submitted it. The preprint can be found here. 

TL;DR: remote web-based eye-tracking works. Downsides: large drop-out rate and less precise than in-lab eye-tracking. Upsides: it is open-source and facilitates recruitment of larger and more diverse samples.

reminders

Join the ManyBabies Slack! 

The #general and #random channels are for network announcements and informal discussions, and there are also many project-specific channels for discussions about study design, analysis, etc.
